BUT it is stuff that the Russian shooting teams used for practice, so it has a wax on it that is just a bit sticky, so it doesn't feed well in semiauto guns. It can be wiped off easily with a paper towel or just used as-is in a bolt action rifle, and for that it works very nicely.

title: For Sale:  BROWNING MODEL 71 50 ALASKAN
postcontent: Hello and thank you for checking out my auction. Up for auction is a very nice Browning Model 71 lever action in .50 Alaskan, These rifles were originally chambered in .348 Winchester. Gunsmiths wanted the Browning 71 due to its durability and strength when converting rifles to 50 Alaskan. This rifle has a half octagon half round barrel measuring at 34", an all steal Schnabel for end, the sights have not been clipped and the engraving on the barrel and action are beautiful. the stock also has a hidden compartment for holding 4 rounds. The .50 Alaskan is a wildcat cartridge developed by Harold Johnson and Harold Fuller of the Kenai Peninsula of Alaska in the 1950s. Johnson based the cartridge on the .348 Winchester in order to create a rifle capable of handling the large bears in Alaska. Design: Harold Johnson necked out the .348 Winchester case to accept a .510" diameter bullet, and Harold Fuller developed the barrel, marrying a .50 caliber barrel to an old Winchester Model 1886 rifle. Since the rifle was designed for use on Alaska’s great bears, Johnson cut 720-grain (47 g) boat-tail .50 BMG bullets in half, seating the 450-grain (29 g) rear half upside down in the fireformed .50-caliber case. It didn’t take Johnson long to find out that the 450-grain truncated shaped “solid” would shoot through a big brown bear from any direction, claiming in 1988, “I never recovered a slug from a bear or moose, no matter what angle the animal was shot at. Harold’s favorite load in the .50 Alaskan was 51.5 grains (3.34 g) of IMR-4198 with a Barnes 400-grain (26 g) flatnose ,jacketed bullet for about 2,100 ft/s (640 m/s) and just under 4,000 ft·lbf (5,400 J)of muzzle energy Shipping/handling is going to be $55 and insurance will be added at 1.75% of the item's value to cover potential damage or loss of the item in shipping. The price is for $2900 therefore, this item will still be subject to shipping and insurance charges. Because of additional paperwork and time to process the shipment,

title: For Sale:  BROWNING MODEL 71 50
postcontent: Hello and thank you for checking out my auction. Up for auction is a very nice Browning Model 71 lever action in .50 Alaskan, These rifles were originally chambered in .348 Winchester. Gunsmiths wanted the Browning 71 due to its durability and strength when converting rifles to 50 Alaskan. This rifle has a half octagon half round barrel measuring at 34", an all steal Schnabel for end, the sights have not been clipped and the engraving on the barrel and action are beautiful. the stock also has a hidden compartment for holding 4 rounds. The .50 Alaskan is a wildcat cartridge developed by Harold Johnson and Harold Fuller of the Kenai Peninsula of Alaska in the 1950s. Johnson based the cartridge on the .348 Winchester in order to create a rifle capable of handling the large bears in Alaska. Design: Harold Johnson necked out the .348 Winchester case to accept a .510" diameter bullet, and Harold Fuller developed the barrel, marrying a .50 caliber barrel to an old Winchester Model 1886 rifle. Since the rifle was designed for use on Alaska’s great bears, Johnson cut 720-grain (47 g) boat-tail .50 BMG bullets in half, seating the 450-grain (29 g) rear half upside down in the fireformed .50-caliber case. It didn’t take Johnson long to find out that the 450-grain truncated shaped “solid” would shoot through a big brown bear from any direction, claiming in 1988, “I never recovered a slug from a bear or moose, no matter what angle the animal was shot at. Harold’s favorite load in the .50 Alaskan was 51.5 grains (3.34 g) of IMR-4198 with a Barnes 400-grain (26 g) flatnose ,jacketed bullet for about 2,100 ft/s (640 m/s) and just under 4,000 ft·lbf (5,400 J)of muzzle energy Shipping/handling is going to be $55 and insurance will be added at 1.75% of the item's value to cover potential damage or loss of the item in shipping. title: For Sale:  Important info on Constitutional carry (update)
postcontent:
Palmetto Gun Rights gathered nearly 9000 petitions to pass Constitutional Carry. 

I delivered those petitions today as part of my testimony before a South Carolina Senate Judiciary subcommittee. 

After listening to two hours of public testimony, the subcommittee approved The Constitutional Carry Act of 2013, S115, by a vote of 5 to 0. The bill now advances to the full Judiciary Committee. 

It would never have received approval without the e-mails, phone calls, and personal contacts that were made by PGR supporters like you. 

Thank you!!! 

So, take a short victory lap, eat an energy bar, and prepare for the next bigger battle in the full Senate Judiciary committee. 

The testimony before the subcommittee was a classic battle of the state vs. the people. 

Everyone who testified against the bill represented some government agency . . . primarily law enforcement.

Everyone who testified for the bill was a member of the general public or a representative of a grass roots group

The fight ahead is going to be extremely tough because nearly every law enforcement agency and municipal association is going to lobby against us.

Funded by your tax dollars either directly or indirectly, these organizations will use your money to try to continue to violate your second amendment right.

The Second Amendment is written to protect our right to keep and bear arms from violation by the government.

So, who will your Senator listen to?

The people whose rights he is sworn to protect, uphold, and defend? 

Or the very politicians and government officials who want to continue to violate those rights?

Contact the chairman Senator Larry Martin at REDACTED today and encourage him to schedule this bill for a hearing immediately! 

Be polite, but be firm! 

There were several verbal amendments made in subcommittee. 

That is always a scary proposition. The devil is in the details. 

We must get the language of these amendments to make sure we still have a good bill. 

And as soon as we are able to take a look at the amendments in writing, I’ll let you know for sure. 

We have a big challenge in the Judiciary Committee with many liberal anti-gun Senators and too many Senators willing to sit the fence. 

These fence sitters will wait to see how the wind blows in their own districts. 

That is why it is critically important for you to contact them now and make it clear that you want them to pass S115 right away. 

You can get the contact information for each of the committee members by clicking here. 

Just like you did with Senator Hembree, make it clear that fence sitting is not an option. 

We at PGR will continue to fight to reclaim our constitutional right to carry a self-defense firearm without infringement. 

We will never sit idly by while our right to self-defense is violated by the men and women in government who are sworn to protect it. 

Thank you for all that you did to bring us this first step toward victory and thanks in advance for what you will do to carry us on to final passage.

This is a new gun. Box papers and three magazines with this D - model. 

The new Beretta Px4 Storm pistol is the most advanced expression of technological and aesthetic features in a semiautomatic sidearm. Built around a modular concept that a pistol can be adapted to different needs and modes of operations, without compromising on ergonomics and the renowned Beretta reliability and performance, the Px4 Storm emphasizes power, ease of handling, performance and reliability.
 Manufactured in three calibers, the Px4 Storm uses an exclusive Beretta designed innovative locked-breech with a rotating barrel system, the strongest action to date.
 The light yet durable frame employs modern thermoplastic technology through the use of technopolymer reinforced fiberglass. Modular structure, ergonomics and
 interchangeability of parts make the Px4 Storm the ideal firearm for law-enforcement use, as well as personal defense.
 1. Accessory Rail: The frame of the Px4 Storm has an integral Picatinny MILSTD-1913 rail for rapid attachment of tactical lights and laser aiming devices.
 2. Visible Automatic Firing Pin Block: The front part of the firing pin is blocked from any forward movement until the trigger is pulled completely back. The block is
 located rearward, far away from the fouling and debris of the breech face. Since the block is visible, the user may ascertain its proper operation at any time. Even if the pistol falls and strikes the ground muzzle down, the firing pin will not strike the primer.
 3. Ambidextrous Safety (Type F): The ambidextrous safety lever, easily accessible by the thumb or a right or left handed shooter, is spring loaded so it’s either positively “on” or “off”. The safety lever also functions as the pistol’s decocking lever. When pushed down, the rear part of the firing pin (striker) is rotated out of alignment with the front part of the firing pin. (NOTE: Type C does not have an external safety/decocking lever). Additional hammer drop catch (half cock notch) prevents striking of the firing pin unit in the remote chance of unintentional hammer drop. 
4. External Hammer Design: A traditional feature of Beretta pistols, this design provides the most energy to the firing pin, virtually eliminating the possibility of
 misfires due to light primer strikes. Also provides an immediate visual and tactile indicator as to the cocked/uncocked status of the pistol.
 5. Individual Size Grips: Pistol may be configured with small, medium or large backstraps to individually fit the hand of each shooter. The backstraps are checkered to ensure a firm grip in both wet or dry shooting conditions. Three backstraps included with every pistol.
 6. Magazine: High capacity steel magazines are durable and drop-free, even when empty, when the magazine button is depressed. Standard flush magazines may be complemented with optional extended magazines that increase the capacity by 3 rounds (1 round for .45 Auto caliber).
 7. Reversible Magazine Release: Multiple-sized, reversible magazine release buttons allow for customization to the individual’s hand size. Small size comes standard on the gun, while medium and large buttons are available as accessories and easy replacement. Each size may be positioned for right-handed or left-handed use.
 8. No Glare Finish: Beretta’s exclusive BrunitonTM non-reflective black coating is a superior corrosion and wear resistant finish.
 9. Simple Field Stripping: Pistol is designed for extremely quick and simple field stripping. Disassembly latch does not remove from the gun, preventing accidental
 dropping and loss. Reassembly is easy and accidental misassembly of parts is prevented by the distinctive design.

 10. Light Technopolymer Frame: The light, yet durable, frame employs modern thermoplastic technology through the use of Corrosion resistant fiberglass reinforced polymer.
 13. Barrrel: The Px4’s unique rotating barrel and locking system dissipates recoil energy radially, reducing felt recoil and muzzle rise. This is the strongest Beretta pistol action. Chrome lined barrels provide extreme corrosion resistance, as well as ease of cleaning. Barrels also feature a deeply recessed combat muzzle crown to protect the rifling. (NOTE: Sub-Compact models feature tilt-barrel locking system and stainless steel construction).

title: For Sale:  CZ 75 P-07 Duty
location: N. Colorado Springs, Colorado Springs, Colorado
postcontent:
This is a new gun, box papers and two magazines. The gun is black, 9mm.

Don't let the "Duty" designation trick you. The P-07 model is a compact handgun -- just as appropriate for concealed carry as it is for uniformed duty.  The abbreviated 3.8" barrel and compact grip allow the Duty to disappear under clothing much more easily than full-sized models. This compact size and polymer frame along with the new slide profile (fully machined from bar stock) reduce weight, making the P-07 Duty a great choice for concealed carry. Easily adaptable to low light use, the Duty features an accessory rail to which a light or laser can be attached.

When designing the polymer frame for the Duty, the decision was made to retain the basic grip shape (circumference, angle, etc.) so popular in the CZ 75 family of handguns. The polymer frame platform eliminated the need for the grip panels that are used on most steel and alloy-framed autos. The absence of the grips resulted in some available space that was used to increase the magazine capacity by 2 rounds. The results speak for themselves -- the flush-fitting magazine of the P-07 Duty holds the same number of rounds that the full-sized versions of the CZ 75 do in both 9mm and .40 S&W.

The most innovative feature of the P-07 duty is the Omega trigger system. The new mechanism was first introduced on the P-07 model. It simplifies the CZ 75 trigger system, uses fewer parts and improves the trigger pull, but the real story is in the versatility it provides for its owner. The Omega system allows users to choose between operating the handgun with a decocking lever (installed) or a manual safety (included) by a simple parts change. 
P-07 DUTY FEATURES
     • 16+1 9mm, 12+1 .40 S&W
     • Convertible, safety or decocker
     • New Omega trigger system
     • Polymer frame with light rail
     • Two magazines

 Guns of Colorado Springs

History of this gun:

I was approached by someone recently who shared the history of the limited run of Wilson "Cave Guns," which were developed for a custom order for Special Forces units heading overseas. According to conversations they had with Wilson Combat, this select run with the SF prefix ended up never being delivered and went up for private sale.

So if you enjoy collecting serial numbers and pistols with some history to them, this is a great pick.
